  <subsection>
    <title>Explorations and Activities</title>
    <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          <em>Using a Logical Equivalency</em>.
          Consider the following proposition:
          <ul>
            \item <em>Proposition</em>. For all integers <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, if 3 does not divide <m>a</m> and 3 does not divide <m>b</m>, then 3 does not divide the product <m>a \cdot b</m>.
          </ul>
          <ol>
            <li>
              <p>
                Notice that the hypothesis of the proposition is stated as a conjunction of two negations (
                <q>3 does not divide <m>a</m> and 3 does not divide <m>b</m></q>).
                Also, the conclusion is stated as the negation of a sentence (
                <q>3 does not divide the product <m>a \cdot b</m>.</q>).
                This often indicates that we should consider using a proof of the contrapositive.
                If we use the symbolic form
                <m>\left( {\mynot Q \wedge \mynot R} \right) \to \mynot P</m> as a model for this proposition,
                what is <m>P</m>, what is <m>Q</m>, and what is <m>R</m>?
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write a symbolic form for the contrapositive of <m>\left( {\mynot Q \wedge \mynot R} \right) \to \mynot P</m>.
              </p>
            </li>
            <li>
              <p>
                Write the contrapositive of the proposition as a conditional statement in English.
              </p>
            </li>
          </ol>
        </p>
        We do not yet have all the tools needed to prove the proposition or its contrapositive.
        However, later in the text,
        we will learn that the following proposition is true.
        <em>Proposition X.</em> Let <m>a</m> be an integer.
        If 3 does not divide <m>a</m>,
        then there exist integers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> such that <m>3x + ay = 1</m>.
        <ol>
          <li>
            <ol>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find integers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> guaranteed by Proposition X when <m>a = 5</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find integers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> guaranteed by Proposition X when <m>a = 2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                  Find integers <m>x</m> and <m>y</m> guaranteed by Proposition X when <m>a = - 2</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ol>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              Assume that Proposition X is true and use it to help construct a proof of the contrapositive of the given proposition.
              In doing so,
              you will most likely have to use the logical equivalency <m>P \to \left( {Q \vee R} \right) \equiv \left( {P \wedge \mynot Q} \right) \to R</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
    </ol>
  </subsection>
